{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[PASS 1 review — T1 Prior-art / novel-architecture justification (overlay; bright-lines: novel architectural pattern + security/signing)]\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (T1 criteria this plan satisfies):\n- Prior-art considered (T1a) — PASS. The parent Context explicitly grounds the design against a broad, relevant prior-art set: \"Gitaly, Sourcegraph gitserver/zoekt, GitHub tarball API, Bazel, ccache, Nix, in-toto.\" These are the right reference systems for a content-addressed, concurrency-safe repo-snapshot+attestation primitive (git-server materialization, content-addressed build caches, supply-chain attestation). Not reinventing in a vacuum.\n- Novelty justified vs established approach (T1b) — PASS. The two genuinely novel choices are each justified against a named established alternative the design REJECTS with a concrete reason: (i) \"read-tree+checkout-index over `git archive`\" is justified by enumerated git-archive faithfulness defects (S1 6d56 Why: drops export-ignore files, omits submodules, returns LFS pointer files, rewrites export-subst) — anti-repackaging is satisfied because the off-the-shelf option is shown insufficient for the attestation guarantee; (ii) \"dropping the rejected PID+heartbeat lease\" in favour of POSIX delete-on-last-close is a documented spike OUTCOME (S2 70c7 triage note item 5; ADR AC). The cross-cutting ADR (authored in S2/S4) capturing \"the decision + rejected alternatives\" is exactly the Rule-of-Three / anti-repackaging artifact T1 asks for, and parent AC8 makes the ADR a closeable obligation.\n- Capability assertion — signing channel (T1c) — PASS/RESOLVED. The \"bind the SHA via the existing manifest channel without a PAYLOAD_VERSION bump / prior signatures still verify\" claim is the one security-sensitive capability assertion, and it is RESOLVED against current source (signing.py: _canonical_payload signs {v,algorithm,ticket_id,manifest}; compute_signature signs the full manifest list; PAYLOAD_VERSION untouched by a manifest step) — already verified on S4 30b3. Not an unverified \"library supports X.\"\n\nFINDING:\n- [ ] Resolve the unverified capability assertion that the chosen `git read-tree`+`checkout-index` primitive yields a FAITHFUL tree for LFS-tracked paths and submodules — name the mechanism, since the primitive does not provide it natively. (criteria: T1c unverified-capability-assertion) — location: S1 `hoot-glove-foyer` (6d56) \"What\" (FAITHFUL tree materialization bullet) + AC2 (\"LFS pointer files are detected (not silently served as content); submodule handling is defined and documented\"); parent \"What\" (attested faithful materialization). evidence: The plan asserts the OUTCOME (\"LFS pointer files are detected\", \"submodule handling is defined\") but the chosen primitive does not deliver it on its own — `git checkout-index` materializes the committed blob content, which for an LFS-tracked path IS the ~130-byte `version https://git-lfs…` pointer (not real content) and for a submodule is a gitlink (mode 160000) that checkout-index does not populate. So the very faithfulness guarantee that justifies the read-tree+checkout-index novelty over `git archive` (S1 Why explicitly lists git-archive's \"returns LFS pointer files / omits submodules\" as the defect it fixes) is, for these two cases, NOT yet shown to be delivered by the replacement — the capability is asserted, not resolved to a named command/decision. This is the load-bearing T1(b)/(c) gap: the anti-`git archive` justification only holds if the replacement actually closes the LFS/submodule faithfulness hole it claims as its motivation. suggested_fix: Add one sentence to S1's \"What\" pinning the mechanism: for LFS, name the detection path (e.g. `.gitattributes` `filter=lfs` and/or the pointer-file magic header) and STATE the decision — fetch real LFS content vs. surface the pointer as a documented known-limitation (and reflect that limitation in S6 docs); for submodules, name the enumeration (e.g. `git ls-tree` gitlink detection) and the recurse-vs-omit decision. If either resolution is non-trivial, carve a short SPIKE so the faithfulness claim that anchors the over-`git-archive` novelty is verified rather than assumed.\n\nNOTE (not a T1 finding): the parent Context cites the \"GitHub tarball API\" as a design influence, but \"Sparse archiving\" / any HTTPS tarball fetch is explicitly Out of scope and no child calls that endpoint — so it is a considered-and-rejected prior-art reference, not an unverified external-capability assertion. Recorded so a later pass does not re-raise it."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782531327615616001,"uuid":"d0cf9ade-4a9b-4879-a53a-c5fa223364cd"}